        "question": "How does Clare feel about the students in her Year 12 science class?",
        "passage": "KE: Mmm. Let's think. So your methodology would involve the children recording what they eat. OK, but you'd also need to have access to the children's medical records and I don't think people would be happy about that; confidentiality would be an issue. If you could get the right data, the conclusions might be significant, but I suspect it's just not going to be easy.\n\nKE: Have you thought about doing an experiment using animals?\n\nKE: Well, the animals don't have to be harmed in any way. It could just be an experiment where they're given a certain diet and the effects are observed.\n\nKE: Yes, you'd have to submit an outline of the experiment and fill in a form, but it's quite straightforward.\n\nRE: But if we found out that, say, a particular diet affects the health of animals, the same thing wouldn't necessarily be true for people, would it?\n\nKE: No that's true, but the findings for any experiment are going to be limited. It's inevitable.\n\nRE: I suppose so. So what animals could I use to investigate the effects of diet? Mice?\n\nKE: Yes. You'd need experimental mice – ones that have been specially bred for experiments.\n\nOK, so what will your experiment be investigating exactly?\n\nRE: Well, something to do with nutrition. So maybe we could look at food supplements... things like extra iron and extra protein, and their impact on health.\n\nKE:Mmm. That might be rather broad. Maybe just look at the effects of one supplement, like sugar, on the health of the mice?\n\nRE: In fact, maybe the focus could be on whether mice can control their own diet.\n\nKE: So, what happens when they have access to more sugar, that they don't really need?\n\nRE: Exactly. Do they eat it or do they decide to leave it?\n\nKE: Great. Then later on, you could do a follow-up experiment adding another variable. Like, you could give some of the mice the chance to be more active, running on a wheel or something, and the others just sit around and don't do much.\n\nRE: Or I could repeat the experiment but change the type of food I provided . . . or use mice with a different genetic structure. But I think your idea would be more interesting, I might think about that some more.\n\nRE: So can I talk through a possible procedure for the experiment where mice are given a sugar supplement?\n\nKE: Sure. I did a similar experiment in college actually.\n\nKE: I'd say about 12. And all young ones, not a mixture of old and young.\n\nRE: OK. And I'd need two groups of equal sizes, so six in each group. And how would I tell them apart? I suppose I could put some sort of tag on one group... or just mark them in some way?\n\nKE: You could use food colouring, that wouldn't hurt them.\n\nRE: Perfect. Then each group would go into a separate cage, and one group, let's call them group A, would be the control group. So they'd just have ordinary mouse food. I suppose you can buy that?\n\nRE: And the other group would have the same as the first group, but they'd also have the extra sugar.\n\nRE: I might be better to give them something like cereal with it.\n\nKE: Hmm. Then you'd need to weigh the mice, I should think once a week. And you'd need an electronic balance.\n\nRE: But we can't hold them on the balance, or it'd affect the reading.\n\nKE: Exactly. So you need something called a weighing chamber to stop the mice from running away. It sounds complicated, but actually you can just use a plastic box with holes in the top.\n\nRE: OK. So once we've measured the weight gain of each mouse we can work out the average for each group, as well as the standard deviation. And then see where we go from there. That sounds cool, I think the students will enjoy it.",
