        "passage": "AN: Sandra, I seem to remember you had some family visitors staying with you recently.\n\nAN: Yeah, that's right. My brother and his family were here a couple of months ago.\n\nAN: OK, good. Well, I wanted to ask for your advice. I got my cousin and her family visiting next month and as I don't have kids, I've no idea where to take them.\n\nAN: Right. What about accommodation? Are they going to stay with you in your flat?\n\nAN: No, thankfully. There wouldn't be room. My cousin wants me to recommend a hotel. Do you know anywhere?\n\nAN: Yes, I do actually. I always recommend people stay at the King's Hotel.\n\nAN: It's about a five minutes walk from Murray Station, so nice and central. It's actually on George Street.\n\nAN: I think they're on quite a tight budget, so how much roughly is it to stay there? If you book a family room, it's about £125 per night. My brother paid for two double rooms in the end, and I think that was around £95 for each room.\n\nAN: Twelve and nine. So I want to organise some trips while they're here. I was thinking of doing a bus tour of the city centre, as none of them have been here before.\n\nAN: Those bus tours are quite expensive. I think it's better to do a walking tour. It gives you a much better feel for the city. There's one that starts from Colton Square. It takes a couple of hours and doesn't cost that much.\n\nAN: If the weather's nice, one thing you could do is visit the old fort. You could get there by boat. The whole trip takes half a day.\n\nAN: That's a really good idea. I'd like to do that myself. And if the weather's bad I was thinking they could go to the science museum. But maybe they could do that when I'm at work.\n\nAN: They're here from Saturday for four nights so Tuesday would be best I think.\n\nAN: And it won't be so crowded then. Saturdays are terrible. I took my kids to the exhibition on old computers there and it was far too crowded. I wanted to go back but it's finished now.\n\nAN: That's a shame. My cousin's kids would have enjoyed that.\n\nAN: There's another one starting soon on space, which looks really good too.\n\nAN: Have you thought about where to take them to eat?\n\nAN: Well, I really like all the food stalls at Clacton Market. My cousin's vegetarian. I know it's one of the best places for that kind of food.\n\nAN: Definitely, and there'll be loads of choices for the kids too. You need to get there quite early, though. At the weekend, most of the stores stop serving lunch at 2.30.\n\nAN: Good point. It's all going to need careful planning. My cousin said she'd love to take the kids to a show at the theatre, but tickets are so expensive.\n\nAN: I know. But you can get some good deals if you book online with bargained tickets for the following day. On some seats there's a 75% discount.\n\nAN: Yeah. There are lots of things you can do for free as well. No need to spend a fortune.\n\nAN: They're coming next month, right? Well, check and see if it's the same weekend as the Roots Music Festival in Blakewell Gardens.\n\nAN: Yeah, check it out online. It's always a family-friendly event and there's no entry charge.\n\nAN: And if you're in Blakewell Gardens, climb Telegraph Hill. You'll be able to look right down on the port. Everyone's always really impressed because it's so huge.\n\nAN: Oh yeah, I've been meaning to do that for ages. I've heard the view's amazing.\n\nAN: Well, that's given me loads of ideas. Thanks so much.",
